>[!error]  Introduction 
> Marx's perception in his book, "Eighteenth Brumaire of Louis Bonaparte", changed. He came to agreement that in countires with democratic instution, the transition capitalism to socialism could be peacful. 

>[!done] Body 

He also believed that this 'relative autonomous state' was not entirely depended on economy but also on religion, culture and technology to sustain itsefl and rule over proletariat. 
It was a situation of temporary equilibrium between the rival warring class, giving state sufficient independence. Though the independce of Bonapartist state(the state of relative autonomy) and its role as 'ostensible mediator' between the rival classes did not mean the state was in position of suspended animation. The bonapartist state, in reality ensured the saftey and stability of bourgeoise society, guaranteeing its rapid development. 
The same thought can be seen [[UPSC/Gramsci|Gramsci]]'s work.
![Pasted image 20221121114422.png](data:image/png;base64,) 
Gramsci argued that the integral state has two entities 
1. Civil Society 
2. Political Society 
Gramsci underlines how the  Civil Society is the site where the hegemon is produced and reproduced in cultural life, through educational institutions, etc, unlike the political society, which rules through coercion, the civil society rules through consent. 
Ralph Miliband view is that of 'instrumentalist theory of state'. Where the state is an instrument of class power.  
Poulantzas views are described as 'structualist theory of state' where the state is itself an arena of class struggle. 

>[!conclusion] 
>It may be questioned
